The G30 wire routing problem is a real mechanical challenge. The phase wires and hall sensor wires exit from the side of the axle rather than through the center, so as the wheel rotates they wrap and eventually bind or break.

Solutions others have used:

> Searched the web
>
> - G30 motor side exit wire routing sim racing wheel clockspring slip ring solution
> - **Done**

Three confirmed solutions for the G30 wire routing problem:

**Option 1 — Slip ring (~$10-15 AliExpress)**
A electrical slip ring allows unlimited rotation while passing power and signals through. Mount it on the shaft, wires connect through it — motor spins freely, wires never wrap. 6-wire slip rings are cheap and handle the 3 phase + 3 hall sensor wires easily. This is the cleanest solution.

**Option 2 — Automotive clockspring**
Exactly what your G35 already has behind the steering wheel. A spiral ribbon cable that allows ~2.75 turns each direction before binding. Sim racing only needs about 1.5 turns lock to lock so a clockspring works perfectly. You could salvage the clockspring from a junkyard car for a few dollars.

**Option 3 — Route wires through hollow axle**
The G30 axle may be hollow or drillable through center — run the wires internally through the axle itself so they exit at the stationary end. Permanent clean solution but requires drilling.

**For your build the slip ring is the obvious answer** — cheap, available on AliExpress, handles all 6 wires, allows unlimited rotation, no mechanical limits on steering angle.

But that's all future G30 upgrade planning. Hoverboard motors first — those wires exit the axle center so zero routing problem.

